        <body>
            <pb n="2" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#i">Interesting Correspondance with M. Alex. de
                        Hum-<lb break="no"/>boldt.</hi>
                </head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>&#x2014;The Ocean Steam Navigation Company of<lb break="yes"/>
                    this city having determined to call the third and fourth<lb break="yes"/>
                    steamers of their line the Franklin and the Humboldt,<lb break="yes"/>
                    authorized their President, Mr. <hi rendition="#k">Sand</hi>, to inform M.<lb break="yes"/>
                    <hi rendition="#k">de Humboldt</hi> of their intention, and beg his sanction<lb break="yes"/>
                    to giving his name to one of their ships. The letter<lb break="yes"/>
                    was forwarded to Berlin through the medium of the<lb break="yes"/>
                    Prussian Minister at Washington, M. <hi rendition="#k">de Gerolt</hi>, and<lb break="yes"/>
                    by the last arrival, the President of the Company<lb break="yes"/>
                    was favored with M. <hi rendition="#k">de Humboldt&#x2019;s</hi> reply, through<lb break="yes"/>
                    the medium of Mr. <hi rendition="#k">Donelson</hi>, our Minister at Ber-<lb break="no"/>lin.
                </p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>We have the pleasure of laying before our readers<lb break="yes"/>
                    a translation of this letter, containing so pleasing an<lb break="yes"/>
                    expression of the generous sentiments of one of the<lb break="yes"/>
                    greatest spirits of the age.
                </p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p><hi rendition="#i">To C. H. Sand, Esq., President of the Ocean Steam<lb break="yes"/>
                    Nav. Co., New York:</hi></p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>Mr. President: Through the medium of my old<lb break="yes"/>
                    Friend, Mr. <hi rendition="#k">de Gerolt</hi>, our Minister in the U. States,<lb break="yes"/>
                    I have to day&#x2014;while occupied with the preparations<lb break="yes"/>
                    for a journey to Paris&#x2014;received the friendly letter,<lb break="yes"/>
                    dated 21st August, with which you have been pleased<lb break="yes"/>
                    to honor me. It <choice><sic>imforms</sic><corr type="editorial">informs</corr></choice> me that a favor has<lb break="yes"/>
                    just been conferred on me, of which I could<lb break="yes"/>
                    not believe myself worthy, of associating <choice><sic>my<lb break="yes"/>
                        my </sic><corr type="editorial">my<lb break="yes"/></corr></choice>name with that of a great citizen, who from my<lb break="yes"/>
                    earliest youth, has been the object of my liveliest<lb break="yes"/>
                    admiration. I venture to request you, sir, to present<lb break="yes"/>
                    the homage of my respectful acknowledgements to<lb break="yes"/>
                    the gentlemen directors of the Ocean Steam Navi-<lb break="no"/>
                    gation Co., who, on the flattering motion of Mr.<lb break="yes"/>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Stephens</hi>, have determined that the fourth ship of<lb break="yes"/>
                    their line of mail steamers between New York and<lb break="yes"/>
                    Bremen shall bear my name.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>In rendering you, Mr. President, the interpreter of<lb break="yes"/>
                    my sentiments, you will be pleased to accept the ex-<lb break="no"/>
                    pression of my gratitude due to your kind co-opera-<lb break="no"/>
                    tion, and the delicacy of your proceedings. Devo-<lb break="no"/>
                    ted as I am, by my travels and labors to the noble<lb break="yes"/>
                    destinies of the new continent, and taking the most<lb break="yes"/>
                    lively interest in the most direct and closest com-<lb break="no"/>
                    mercial intercourse between the United States and<lb break="yes"/>
                    my country, I put the highest value on the honor<lb break="yes"/>
                    which you confer upon me, in the decline of a life<lb break="yes"/>
                    which has had no other merit than that of a coura-<lb break="no"/>
                    geous perseverance in the love <choice><sic>of a</sic><corr type="editorial">for the</corr></choice> good and free-<lb break="no"/>
                    dom of opinion.
                </p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        I have the honor to remain,
                        <lb break="yes"/>
                        With the highest consideration,
                        <lb break="yes"/>
                        Sir, your ob’t humble servant.
                        <lb break="yes"/>
                        ALEX. DE HUMBOLDT.
                    </salute>
                </closer>
            </div>
